    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-12-10T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-12-10T18:00:00-05:00" n="662"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d662">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 (D) Regulations/869b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-10T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 10, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>531. The Radio Bulletin of December 10 carries information in regard to a
                    proclamation signed by the President<note n="89" xml:id="d662fn89">Dated
                        December 10, <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_232">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 232</ref>.</note> placing under license
                    exportation from the United States of iron and steel as defined in an Executive
                    Order issued on that day;<note n="90" xml:id="d662fn90">No.8607; <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_233">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 233</ref>.</note> also the text of an
                    announcement made by the White House on this subject.<note n="91"
                        xml:id="d662fn91">See press release issued by the Department of State, <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_232">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 232</ref>.</note> The action taken is
                    described accurately in the text of the official announcements here and it is
                    suggested that, if inquiries are made of you, you so state, emphasizing that the
                    action taken rests upon the national defense requirements of the United States
                    and that licenses for exports to destinations other than the British Empire and
                    the Western Hemisphere will be granted for the present and in so far as the
                    interests of national defense permit in amounts approximating usual or pre-war
                    exports.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
